title: For Sale:  Russian Type 2 Milled AK47 NUMBERS MATCHING Type
postcontent: This is a Russian Type 2 AK47. It is a reweld build from a PLO parts kit. The reweld was done by Matt Yeamans (aka turbothis on the forums).  This rifle was built from a demilled parts kit. Unlike most of the PLO kit builds you see around, this one has ALL MATCHING SERIAL NUMBERS. They are all original serials, nothing has been force matched or faked with unserialed parts. See the pics of the serials for verification. I was able to find serials on the front receiver stub, bolt, carrier, top cover, gas tube, buttstock lower tang (so even the rear receiver stub was the right one for this rifle), and the recoil spring assembly. The rear sight leaf has the same serial, it was hand scratched and is very faint. I am unable to get it to show up in pictures.  The barrel on this rifle is in surprisingly great shape. See the pics for a "bullet test" picture. The bore is bright and shiney with strong rifling.  The new center section of the receiver was finished with cold blue. The rest of the finish was left untouched. I did my best to blend the cold blue with the original finish. It has a very cool "battlefield pickup" look to it that is all original.  US made parts on this rifle are the FCG (Tapco G2), receiver (reweld receiver counts as US made), and the gas piston. The piston is a replica early type fluted gas piston. I also have the original Russian gas piston, which I will include with the rifle. Not lloking for trades, but if you need it shipped it must go through a dealer.

title: For Sale:  ** REDUCED ** CUSTOM TTN/CIMARRON SXS 1878 HAMMER GUN, COLOR-CASED WITH ACTION WORK - PITTSBURGH
postcontent: Customized by Steve Young (AKA "Nate Kiowa Jones"), a renowned Cowboy Action Shooting gunsmith, this 12ga is a modern clone of the venerable Colt 1878.This Cimarron/TTN is a the top SXS for the CAS shooters shooting in the Classic Cowboy category. This is the gun that 5 time World champ T Bone Dooley used. Steve posted this to the SASS Wire back in 2004:Nate Kiowa Jones#6765SASS Wire Vet Member # 2404posted May 18, 2004 12:55 PM"I have one of these TNN guns here. I personally think it will be the ruler of the Classic Cowboy shotguns. TNN has addressed several issues with this gun. As mentioned, the hammers are close for easier one-handed cocking. Even just out of the box it is do-able. Mild Bill was concerned that the gun couldn`t be opened with it cocked. Not to worry, the lever works under the hammers and it will open and with these large heavy hammers, it will be easy to reduce the hammer springs even more. As Old Scout mentioned it points well. The Liberty`s and the newer Rossi`s don`t have enough drop in the stock. They tend to shoot high for most people. When I shoulder this gun there is no rib visible, just bead. If you see rib, you will shot high. The next issue is there is no tang safety or hammer blocks to complicate the gun. That was the biggest problem with the Liberty. All that extra junk makes it hard to tune. The internals of this gun are very similar to the originals. Next, this is a 3" chambered long forcing cone gun. Strawberry lars knows shotguns but I do disagree with him about 3" chambered long forcing guns compared to 2&3/4" short cone guns. Felt recoil in minimal with this guns. I talked to one of the guys at TNN and they tell me that this gun has passed the drop test, but he also mentioned that they did a 12/20 test. They dropped a 20ga round in a chamber and then a 12ga round on top of it and then test fired the gun. He tells me that the barrel showed no damage but they did bust the stock. The barrels are heavy. They are of the newer stronger mono block design. Basically, the chamber area is all one piece. I not sure how the side locks are mounted on the original but this gun has them positively attached to the receiver metal, not the wood. The problem with the liberty locks is they attach through the wood and over time they get loose or they get tighten to a point that one trigger will shoot both barrels.It also has a really cool roll-over steel butt-plate. We shot it Saturday with everything from 3" mags to 50gr black powder loads. Hulls just fell right out. The only negative I can see is it needs a larger front bead. (they have since added the big #4 bead) I do think this gun will be the gun for classic. I am currently doing an action job on this one for a customer."HERE IS THE CUSTOM WORK DONE TO THIS SHOTGUN, IN STEVE'S OWN WORDS:"As to what I have done with this gun, they come stock as all blue so the first step for the color-cased guns is to take them apart de-burred and de-horn and send everything out for a true bone meal and charcoal color-case hardening. Once I get the parts back The next step is refitting and polishing the parts so the gun will run with lighter springs. Then I just lighten the hammer springs, and the firing pin springs. The old V type latch spring and the sear springs are the weakest parts for hard CAS use so they are changed out to hand fitted piano wire springs They dont break. When finished the gun easily cock both hammers at the same time with one thumb. The latch lever will open easier and the barrels will fall open wide of their own weight. For the barrels, I polish the chambers and chamfer the chamber mouths for easy loading and unloading. For the right handed shooters, I reverse the triggers, front trigger on the left and the rear trigger on the right. With the triggers setup like this, the front trigger is on the left side and once it is pulled the finger can easily slip straight back to the rear which is now on the right side. You don't have to reach around the front trigger to get to the back trigger. I think this is a faster setup than even the single trigger guns because you don't have to let up on the trigger to get a reset required of the single trigger gun. This setup can make it seem almost like both trigger were pulled at the same time."Finally, I had my local gunsmith very slightly shorten the stock and add a recoil pad, per Steve's instructions:"Also the stocks on most of the CAS SXS guns are designed for aerial targets. When you point them toward the ground the positive toe of those stocks tends to dig into your shoulder when you fire. This will eventually cause the shooter to let the stock move down on the shoulder which brings the front end up. The shot goes high. Savvy shooters will lean way into the shot but that usually doesn't work for the lady shooters. So, now that positive toe is nailing them. For the shotguns besides shortening the stock, I like cut them so the pad is about 5 degrees negative. That helps take some of the felt recoil away shooting at our ground targets."Actually, I don't shoot in Cowboy Action Shooting...I just love this gun! It's the one Steve McQueen used in "The Magnificent Seven" and Lee Marvin used in "The Professionals"! The action is like glass and it's a hoot to shoot. The only reason I'm selling is I badly need the cash. You're not going to find another classic like this - anywhere!The price for this beauty is $800, cash or CREDIT CARD. I also have some cases of Winchester "Low recoil, low noise" shells available to the buyer. I'd prefer not to ship but, if necessary, I'll add actual shipping costs.This gun is in Greenfield.Contact me at REDACTED.

title: For Sale:  LWRC M6IC Limited Edition, The Cadillac  of AR-15's
postcontent: I have a brand new, unfired, limited edition LWRC M6IC, IC-DI 5.56 mm, 16" barrel, AR-15. Does not include the custom sights seen on the rifle, although I might be willing to throw them in for just $50 more. Gun enthusiasts, top notch law enforcement, and the highest level military will tell you that LWRC is basically the Cadillac of AR-15's. Well, haha, I would actually call it the Ferrari of AR's. This is honestly the baddest ass AR I've ever seen, and not merely because of the LWRC name. It has an absoluetly gorgeous limited edition burnt bronze finish; no other rifle looks like it.  Being a rifle designed for the military, it already has a built in semi auto, AND full auto option on the safety selector switch, if you so choose to convert to full auto with just a few extra parts. Full length top rail from the rear of the receiver all the way to the tip of the hand/heat guard at the end of the barrell. More rails can be added to the bottom and both sides of the guard from tip to tail. More rail space/mounts than you could ever possibly need. Truthfully, forget the cheap-ass $700-$800 AR's, you're much better off investing in something like this, one of the top notch rifles you can find on the planet. The one place you should absolutely not be cheap, I mean the ONE place, is when you're buying a rifle like this. I'm highly disappointed that I have to get rid of this rifle, before getting to even try it out, but life calls and I need the money for my kids/family for Christmas. Due to this, I am really trying to get the full price listed, but there could possibly be a little bit of wiggle room depending on how much of a response I get. That is, as long as it's a truly reasonable offer, as I do have it priced to sell already, especially considering it is a rifle with such high demand/reputation. Do yourself a HUGE favor, get an early Christman present, and get the nicest semi-auto (or full-auto if so chosen) rifle money can buy!!! I promise you will not be dissapointed with this bad boy.
